definition.value: A compound of iron and sulfate in which the ratio of iron(2+) to sulfate ions is 1:1. Various hydrates occur naturally - most commonly the heptahydrate, which loses water to form the tetrahydrate at 57degreeC and the monohydrate at 65degreeC.
(8E,12Z)-10-hydroperoxy-8,12-octadecadienoic acid with S-configuration at C-10.

A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of iron(2+) sulfate. It is obtained from the heptahydrate by heating above 65degreeC. It is used as a source of iron in the treatment of iron-deficiency anaemia (generally in solid-dosage treatments; for liquid-dosage treatments, the heptahydrate is normally used).
A compound which increases either the number of red cells or the amount of haemoglobin in the blood.

A hydrate that is the heptahydrate form of iron(2+) sulfate. It is used as a source of iron in the treatment of iron-deficiency anaemia (generally in liquid-dosage treatments; for solid-dosage treatments, the monohydrate is normally used).
(E)-3,7,11,15-tetramethylhexadec-2-en-1-yl diphosphate in which both stereocentres have (R)-configuration.
A polyprenol phosphate that is the monophosphate derivative of phytol.
A quercetin O-glucoside that is quercetin with a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 4'.
A ketoaldonic acid that is the 2-dehydro-3-deoxy derivative of L-galactonic acid.
A triglyceride formed by acylation of the three hydroxy groups of glycerol with palmitoleic acid.
A hydroxyisoflavanone that is isoflavanone carrying two hydroxy substituents located at positions 4' and 7.
A ketoaldonic acid that is the L-threo-isomer of 3-deoxyhex-2-ulopyranosonic acid.
A triglyceride formed by acylation of the three hydroxy groups of glycerol with linoleic acid.
A triglyceride formed by acylation of the three hydroxy groups of glycerol with linolenic acid.
A triglyceride in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 3 are specified as oleoyl while that at position 2 is specified as palmitoyl.
The R-enantiomer of 1,2-dioleoyl-3-palmitoylglycerol.
A triglyceride in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl while that at position 3 is specified as palmitoyl.
A 1,3-diglyceride in which both acyl groups are specified as palmitoleoyl.
A 1,3-diglyceride in which both acyl groups are specified as linoleoyl.
An L-alpha-amino acid obtained by enzyme-mediated intramolecular cyclisation of L-arginine.
A 1,3-diglyceride in which both acyl groups are specified as linolenoyl.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which both acyl groups are specified as palmitoleoyl.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which both acyl groups are specified as linoleoyl.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which both acyl groups are specified as linolenoyl.
An omega-carboxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the least hindered carboxy group of mesaconic acid.
Any rhamnoside that exists in the furanose form.
Any rhamnofuranoside that has alpha-D-configuration.
A quercetin O-glycoside that is quercetin attached to a alpha-D-rhamnofuranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
The (3R)-diastereomer of citramalyl-CoA.
A sulfide mineral with formula AsFeS. It is the most abundant and widespread arsenic mineral.
A D-rhamnofuranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A quercetin O-glycoside that is quercetin attached to a alpha-L-fucopyranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
A carbohydrate phosphate that is the 6-O-phospho derivative of 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-gluconic acid.
A 1,3-diglyceride in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 3 are specified as oleoyl and palmitoyl respectively (the S-stereoisomer).
A 1,3-diglyceride in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 3 are specified as palmitoyl and oleoyl respectively (the R-stereoisomer).
A 1,3-diglyceride in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 3 are specified as oleoyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A nitrohydrocarbon that is an alkane in which one of the hydrogens has been replaced by a nitro group.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 2 and 3 are specified as palmitoyl and oleoyl respectively.
The (S)-enantiomer of sarin; the more potent enantiomer of racemic sarin, a nerve agent that is employed as a chemical warfare agent.
The (S)-enantiomer of sarin; the less active enantiomer of racemic sarin, a nerve agent that is employed as a chemical warfare agent.
A phosphinic ester that is the isopropyl ester of methylphosphonofluoridic acid.
A ring assembly based on a 1,4-diphenylbenzene skeleton and its substituted derivatives thereof.

A cyclic oligonucleotide consisting of TGCGAATTCGCT and TGCGAATTCGCT strands of DNA linked by hydrogen bonding between the base pairs and also covalently via two disulfanediyldiethane-1,2-diyl linkages between the N-3 atoms of the terminal thymidine residues.
A cyclohexadienecarboxylic acid that is cyclohexa-1,5-diene-1-carboxylic acid carrying two hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 4 (the 3R,4R-stereoisomer).
A quercetin O-glycoside that is quercetin attached to a beta-L-rhamnopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
An oligonucleotide which has a cyclic structure with no terminus.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 4-O-(beta-L-Araf-(1->2)-beta-L-Araf-(1->2)-beta-L-Araf)-cis-L-Hyp.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 4-O-(beta-L-Araf)-cis-L-Hyp.
A monocarboxylic acid that is (2E,4Z,6E)-4-methoxy-6-methylhepta-2,4,6-trienoic acid substituted at position 7 by an 8-hydroxy-1,2,3,4-tetrahydrodibenzofuran-1-yl group.
